="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-measurement/">Party Dress <span>(17)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#544">Transparent corsets  <span>(4)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="25"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-cutting-a-mock-up/">Corset with Drapery <span>(20)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="26"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-and-the-throw-over-sewing-technique/">Corset with Integral Straps <span>(27)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="34"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model/">Corset with 3-Part Cups <span>(22)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="76"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-5/">Corset with a Fancy Cut-Out <span>(22)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#3082">Decoration Techniques  <span>(9)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="83"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials/">Rhinestones Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="84"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-glue-on-half-pearls/">Additional Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="85"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-thick-decoration-element/">Thick Decoration Elements <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="86"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials-2/">Wedding Dress Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="87"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong><em>Dressmaker’s Treasury&nbsp;</em></strong><strong>is a collection of key tools and skills which every dressmaker needs for successful work.</strong></p><p><strong>I am offering you a great instrument to help you acquire more confidence for fulfilling your creative projects!&nbsp;</strong>You will no longer have any fear of complex sophisticated garments! You will learn to work with mock-ups, make crinolines of non-standard shapes, and sew various kinds of fabric cases for petticoats to enhance the fullness of the main skirt.</p><p><strong>Our main goal at the Corset Academy&nbsp;</strong>is to teach you how to sew wedding and evening garments. And I want you to be able to sew a high-quality garment within a relatively short time.</p><p><strong>I don’t want you to spend lots of time on doing complicated calculations and making basic skirt patterns!</strong></p><p><strong>All necessary materials are included in the course:</strong></p><ul><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in the actual size (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in half the actual size for sewing mock-ups and designing new skirt models (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculation of all parameters required for cutting a trapeze-shaped skirt, a half-circle skirt, and a full-sweep skirt (HTML). These tables contain 18 tabs for calculating necessary parameters for the mentioned types of skirts, horizontal and vertical ruffles, falbalas, and the elastic waistband skirt.</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculations with fixed parameters for the trapeze-shaped skirt, the half-circle skirt, and the full-sweep skirt (HTML);</h4></li></ul><h4>Fixed parameters (i.e. measurements) allow you to quickly calculate necessary data for cutting ruffles and falbalas for a skirt of a certain size: consumption of main fabric, lining fabric, decorative materials, etc.</h4><p><strong>Our new course&nbsp;<em>Dressmaker’s Treasury. Wedding Skirts and Petticoats&nbsp;</em>is a collection of important methods and skills which every dressmaker must know in order to achieve good results. It will be equally helpful for beginners and for experienced professionals!</strong></p><p><strong>Every professional dressmaker knows that sewing complex wedding skirts&nbsp;</strong>is not just about sewing together kilometers of fabric. The key thing is correct calculations and your ability to “foresee” the final results and related fabric consumption well before you start cutting and sewing.</p><p>I would also like to emphasize that the skirt from this course is merely a foundation for your own masterpieces. Let your creativity bloom!</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Enjoy it!</strong></p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;6h 12m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-40-making-complicated-mock-up-petticoats-overview-of-petticoat-styles/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-40-making-complicated-mock-up-petticoats-overview-of-petticoat-styles/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2018-05-08T18:49:07+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2018-05-08T18:49:07+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2018"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 40. Making Complicated Mock-Up Petticoats. Overview of Petticoat Styles."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 40. Making Complicated Mock-Up Petticoats. Overview of Petticoat Styles."><meta itemprop="description" content="In this chapter, we are going to talk about petticoats or inner constructions custom-made for individual skirts to help them hold the desired shape."><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding Skirts and Petticoats. Practical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding skirts and petticoats. practical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 40. Making Complicated Mock-Up Petticoats. Overview of Petticoat Styles.</h1><p><strong>In this chapter, we are going to talk about petticoats or inner constructions custom-made for individual skirts to help them hold the desired shape. </strong></p><p><strong>Here is the right order for making a skirt like this: </strong>first you choose a petticoat or crinoline of the desired volume (bottom diameter) and then you adjust it to the desired shape with the help of a fabric casing. And afterwards, at the very end of the process, you take measurements off the resulting construction and make a pattern for the face skirt based on them.</p><p><strong>Beginners often make one and the same mistake when they first sew a skirt and then try to find a matching inner construction for it. </strong>It is an absolutely wrong path. It is very complicated and does not always lead to good results. You must always think over the inner construction before you start working on a garment worn over a petticoat.</p><p><strong>Let us see what kinds of basic petticoats there are and what shapes and sizes they have. </strong>There are lots and lots of kinds of petticoats available today. <strong>The key thing</strong> is to understand what kind of an inner construction you need and why and then buy or make something similar.</p><p><strong>The smallest petticoat you can walk in has a bottom hoop with a length of 190cm. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Here is a half-scale mock-up of this petticoat: </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>This is as small as it gets. </strong></p><p>I recommend this petticoat to those brides who refuse wearing petticoats with hoops and yet look for a skirt with a noticeable amount of flare.</p><p>They usually order a full gathered skirt or a trapeze-shaped skirt but ask for a petticoat without hoops made of several layers of tulle.</p><p>I never manage to convince them that they are going to feel very hot in a tulle petticoat without a hoop down the bottom and, moreover, that they are going to keep stumbling and getting tangled in all those inner layers.</p><p>Only after trying on a ready skirt with a petticoat and then without it, the bride usually agrees for a petticoat with a single hoop down the bottom.</p><p><strong>With this in regard, I believe it is absolutely compulsory to have a petticoat like this in your atelier if you sew for clients. </strong></p><p><strong>It is even better to have one or several petticoats with a 230-250cm long bottom hoop. </strong></p><p><strong>These are the most comfortable petticoats for wide full skirts. </strong>And it will be just great if you can get yourself a basic petticoat like that with many removable hoops from top down to the very bottom.</p><p><strong>You will be able to use any desired number of hoops depending on what functions the petticoat is supposed to perform. </strong></p><p><strong>Below are a picture of the original petticoat and a picture of its half-scale mock-up. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image005.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image007.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>As for me, I have used petticoats with a 250-270cm bottom hoop in quite many cases. </strong>I would make a fabric casing for it if the skirt was supposed to be very full, similar to the way we did for the full gathered skirt. I will explain how to calculate a fabric casing like this and related fabric consumption a little later. I will also remind you how to assemble a full gathered skirt.</p><p><strong>Let us one more time go through the most common lengths of bottom hoops used in basic petticoats. </strong></p><p><strong>The smallest possible petticoat </strong>is a petticoat with a 190cm long bottom hoop. It is followed by petticoats with 230cm long, 250cm long, and 270cm long bottom hoops, and then petticoats with 300cm to 350cm long bottom hoops. Basic petticoats are rarely ever made with bottom hoops exceeding 350-400cm.</p><p><strong>The pictures below show a petticoat with a 300cm long bottom hoop and a half-scale mock-up of it. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image009.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image011.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p>Petticoats of this shape with a bottom hoop longer than 400cm are used very rarely, only in some extraordinary cases. <strong>That is why dressmakers normally use different kinds of fabric casings to achieve the desired fullness of a skirt with a hem length of 400cm and above. </strong>The desired volume is mostly achieved with the help of ruffles made of mesh fabric of varied density. The bottom ruffles are usually made of high-density mesh fabric to make the hem of the skirt as full and delicate as possible, while the top ruffles are made of softer mesh fabric to fill in all hollows and form the desired shape.</p><p><strong>Useful tip:</strong> the bottom ruffles of a fabric casing made of high-density mesh fabric will become even stiffer and hold the shape of a heavy skirt very well if you finish their hem edges with bias tape.</p><p><strong>Here are several pictures of fabric casings like this: </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image013.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image015.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image017.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Up until now I have been showing you examples of petticoats flared right from the waist. </strong>But what should you do if your dress is supposed to flare from the hips?</p><p><strong>There are special petticoats for dresses like this where the flare begins at the level where the narrow part of the dress stops. </strong>The flared part can begin anywhere you want.</p><p><strong>Below are examples of petticoats with various levels of flare: </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image019.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image020.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Using such petticoats implies certain rules and limitations: </strong></p><p><strong>- Firstly,</strong> such petticoats are usually made by customizing standard factory-made petticoats. Everything depends on the style of the dress, the shape of the skirt, and the level where the flare begins.</p><p><strong>- Secondly,</strong> you can create the desired flare just with the help of hoops only on petticoats with a bottom hoop length of 300-350cm max. The lower the flare begins, the smaller the bottom hoop can be.</p><p><strong>- And, thirdly,</strong> fullness can be increased further only with the help of a fabric casing with ruffles.</p><p><strong>You can see different types of fabric casings for this category of petticoats in the pictures below: </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image024.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image026.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image028.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image030.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Petticoats for skirts with a train are an absolutely independent category. </strong></p><p><strong>I can say it with full confidence relying on my many years’ experience that there is no such a thing as a standard universal ready-made petticoat with a train! </strong></p><p>All standard petticoats have some or other disadvantages related to their shape and their ability to support the garment, and they are also quite expensive, too. <strong>For this reason,</strong> it almost always makes sense to make a custom petticoat yourself or sew a special fabric casing with a train for a basic ready-made petticoat.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image032.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image034.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>It is very important to remember about garment balance here. </strong>The inner construction of the skirt must be strong enough to carry the weight of the train without sinking in and letting the heavy back outweigh and lift the lighter front. I will tell you how to make a petticoat like this in the tutorials to follow.</p><p><strong>In conclusion, let me give you a piece of advice: </strong>whenever you are thinking over an inner skirt construction, remember about the material you are going to use for the face. Any cascading, hard, or horizontal ruffles put on the fabric casing or on the petticoat will show through thin face fabric. Hard ruffles on the fabric casing may result in unwanted bumps and dents on the face layer.</p><p><strong>And that is why stiff hard ruffles of the fabric casing are usually covered up by several layers of tulle regardless of what material the skirt itself is made of. </strong>This allows you to create the desired fullness while making the surface of the underskirt smooth. The shape of the face skirt will not get distorted with an inner construction like this!</p><p><strong>The key rule related to all kinds of petticoats and inner skirt constructions: </strong>first create the shape and fullness and then try to give a smooth surface to the top layer of the petticoat. It reminds me of covering walls with wallpaper: you need to first plaster the wall to make it smooth if you want the wallpaper to stick to the surface evenly without bubbles and creases.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image036.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>There is another very important moment which often gets neglected. What kind of a waistband should the inner skirt construction have? </strong>If the face skirt is going to be light and the inner construction is not very heavy either, then you can simply use waistband elastic or plain wide elastic. <strong>It is, however, a lot better to provide for a robust waistband for the entire inner construction in advance!</strong></p><p><strong>As you can judge </strong>from all said above, it usually takes more time and more materials to make the inner construction than the face skirt itself.</p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation Tables of All Parameters Required:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sun/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/halfSun/index.htm" target="_blank">Half-Circle Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/dlina/index.htm" target="_blank">Full-Sweep Skirt</a> </strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation&nbsp;Tables with Fixed Parameters:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sunFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/halfSunFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Half-Circle Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/dlinaFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Full-Sweep Skirt</a></strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Sewing patterns are in PDF format.</p><p>To print sewing patterns open the files, press “print” and choose “<strong>PRINT IN ACTUAL SIZE</strong>“.</p><p>In each&nbsp;file the pattern is divided &nbsp;to A4 paper sheets for home printer.</p><h3>Skirt Patterns:</h3><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Patterns/flaredSkirt.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset